  "sections": {
    "Background": {
      "text": "Defined as a platelet count >450,000/microL.",
      "subsections": {
        "Reactive_thrombocytosis_(RT)": {
          "text": "Most common cause of thrombocytosis, accounting for 85% of cases.\nA reaction to another process, such as inflammation, infection, cancer, or iron deficiency.\nRarely causes complications even with extremely elevated platelet counts (>1,000,000/microL).",
          "tables": []
        },
        "Autonomous_thrombocytosis_(AT)": {
          "text": "Accounts for 15% of cases\nA primary problem that results from\nmyeloproliferative disorders\nor\nmyelodysplastic syndromes\n, such as essential\nthrombocytopenia\nor\npolycythemia vera\n.\nComplications, such as bleeding and/or thrombosis, are more likely with AT than with RT so it is clinically important to differentiate reactive thrombocytosis versus autonomous thrombocytosis.\nThere are no diagnostic studies to differentiate RT versus AT.",
          "tables": []
        }
      },
      "tables": [],
      "links": [
